<solution><div><h3>Worked solution</h3>
<p><alert>Statement forms of axioms:</alert> <br/>Give the statement form of each axiom given in the problem. <br/>Let a: "Albert orders a dessert", b: "Bernard orders a dessert", and c: "Charles orders a dessert". <br/>1. "If Albert orders a dessert, Bernard orders one too": a implies b <br/>2. "Every day, either Bernard or Charles, but not both, orders a dessert": (b and not c) or (not b and c) <br/>3. "Albert or Charles, or both, order dessert daily": a or c <br/>4. "If Charles orders dessert, Albert does the same": c implies a</p>
<hr/>
<p><alert>Fill in truth table:</alert> Here are the truth tables of each of these statements </p>
<p>Truth table of <m>a \implies b</m>: <m>{\begin{array}{c|c|c} a &amp; b &amp; a\,{\text{ implies }}\, b\\ \hline \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \end{array}}</m> </p>
<p>Truth table of ( <m> b \land \neg c</m> ) <m>\lor</m>  ( <m>\neg b \land c</m> ): <m>{\begin{array}{c|c|c} b &amp; c &amp; b\,{\text{ and }}\, {\rm not}\left( c \right)\,{\text{ or }}\, {\rm not}\left( b \right)\,{\text{ and }}\, c\\ \hline \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} \\ \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} \end{array}}</m></p>
<p>Truth table of <m> a \lor c </m>: <m>{\begin{array}{c|c|c} a &amp; c &amp; a\,{\text{ or }}\, c\\ \hline \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} \\ \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \end{array}}</m> </p>
<p>Truth table of <m> c \implies a </m>: <m>{\begin{array}{c|c|c} a &amp; c &amp; c\,{\text{ implies }}\, a\\ \hline \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{F} &amp; \mathbf{T} \\ \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} &amp; \mathbf{T} \end{array}}</m></p>
<hr/>
<p><alert>Answer to the enigma:</alert> Who order a dessert and who does not order a dessert? <br/>We deduction that the interpretation that makes all four statement forms true is the second line from the truth table. <br/>One can see that only "a" and "b" are true and "c" is false. Therefore, Albert and Bernard order dessert but not Charles.</p></div></solution>
